<doc id="1114832" wikidata="Q8026989" url="?curid=1114832" title="Wirral Hundred">
<text>The Hundred of Wirral is the ancient administrative area for the Wirral Peninsula. Its name is believed to have originated from the &quot;Hundred of Wilaveston&quot;, the historic name for Willaston, which was an important assembly point in the Wirral Hundred during the Middle Ages. 
The &quot;ton&quot; suffix in a place name normally indicates a previous use as a meeting location for officials. During its existence, the hundred was one of the Hundreds of Cheshire.

Since local government reorganisation, implemented on 1 April 1974, the area is split between Merseyside (Metropolitan Borough of Wirral) and Cheshire.

