<doc id="1115052" wikidata="Q255166" url="?curid=1115052" title="Kullback–Leibler divergence">
<text>In mathematical statistics, the Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence (also called relative entropy and I-divergence), denoted formula_1, is a type of statistical distance: a measure of how much a model probability distribution is different from a true probability distribution . Mathematically, it is defined as

:formula_2

A simple interpretation of the KL divergence of from is the expected excess surprise from using as a model instead of when the actual distribution is . While it is a measure of how different two distributions are and is thus a &quot;distance&quot; in some sense, it is not actually a metric, which is the most familiar and formal type of distance. In particular, it is not symmetric in the two distributions (in contrast to variation of information), and does not satisfy the triangle inequality. Instead, in terms of information geometry, it is a type of divergence, a generalization of squared distance, and for certain classes of distributions (notably an exponential family), it satisfies a generalized Pythagorean theorem (which applies to squared distances).

Relative entropy is always a non-negative real number, with value 0 if and only if the two distributions in question are identical. It has diverse applications, both theoretical, such as characterizing the relative (Shannon) entropy in information systems, randomness in continuous time-series, and information gain when comparing statistical models of inference; and practical, such as applied statistics, fluid mechanics, neuroscience, bioinformatics, and machine learning.

== Introduction and context ==
Consider two probability distributions and . Usually, represents the data, the observations, or a measured probability distribution. Distribution represents instead a theory, a model, a description or an approximation of . The Kullback–Leibler divergence formula_1 is then interpreted as the average difference of the number of bits required for encoding samples of using a code optimized for rather than one optimized for . Note that the roles of and can be reversed in some situations where that is easier to compute, such as with the expectation–maximization algorithm (EM) and evidence lower bound (ELBO) computations.

== Etymology ==
The relative entropy was introduced by Solomon Kullback and Richard Leibler in as &quot;the mean information for discrimination between formula_4 and formula_5 per observation from formula_6&quot;, where one is comparing two probability measures formula_7, and formula_8 are the hypotheses that one is selecting from measure formula_7 (respectively). They denoted this by formula_10, and defined the &quot;&#x27;divergence&#x27; between formula_6 and formula_12&quot; as the symmetrized quantity formula_13, which had already been defined and used by Harold Jeffreys in 1948. In , the symmetrized form is again referred to as the &quot;divergence&quot;, and the relative entropies in each direction are referred to as a &quot;directed divergences&quot; between two distributions; Kullback preferred the term discrimination information. The term &quot;divergence&quot; is in contrast to a distance (metric), since the symmetrized divergence does not satisfy the triangle inequality. Numerous references to earlier uses of the symmetrized divergence and to other statistical distances are given in . The asymmetric &quot;directed divergence&quot; has come to be known as the Kullback–Leibler divergence, while the symmetrized &quot;divergence&quot; is now referred to as the Jeffreys divergence.

==Definition==
For discrete probability distributions and defined on the same sample space, formula_14 the relative entropy from to is defined to be
:formula_15

which is equivalent to

:formula_16

In other words, it is the expectation of the logarithmic difference between the probabilities and , where the expectation is taken using the probabilities .

Relative entropy is only defined in this way if, for all , formula_17 implies formula_18 (absolute continuity). Otherwise, it is often defined as but the value formula_19 is possible even if formula_20 everywhere, provided that formula_21 is infinite in extent. Analogous comments apply to the continuous and general measure cases defined below.

Whenever formula_22 is zero the contribution of the corresponding term is interpreted as zero because

:formula_23

For distributions and of a continuous random variable, relative entropy is defined to be the integral

:formula_24 

where and denote the probability densities of and .

More generally, if and are probability measures on a measurable space formula_14 and is absolutely continuous with respect to , then the relative entropy from to is defined as

:formula_26

where formula_27 is the Radon–Nikodym derivative of with respect to , i.e. the unique almost everywhere defined function on formula_21 such that formula_29 which exists because is absolutely continuous with respect to . Also we assume the expression on the right-hand side exists. Equivalently (by the chain rule), this can be written as

:formula_30

which is the entropy of relative to . Continuing in this case, if formula_31 is any measure on formula_32 for which densities and with formula_33 and formula_34 exist (meaning that and are both absolutely continuous with respect to formula_35), then the relative entropy from to is given as

:formula_36

Note that such a measure formula_31 for which densities can be defined always exists, since one can take formula_38 although in practice it will usually be one that in the context like counting measure for discrete distributions, or Lebesgue measure or a convenient variant thereof like Gaussian measure or the uniform measure on the sphere, Haar measure on a Lie group etc. for continuous distributions. 
The logarithms in these formulae are usually taken to base 2 if information is measured in units of bits, or to base if information is measured in nats. Most formulas involving relative entropy hold regardless of the base of the logarithm.

Various conventions exist for referring to formula_39 in words. Often it is referred to as the divergence &quot;between&quot; and , but this fails to convey the fundamental asymmetry in the relation. Sometimes, as in this article, it may be described as the divergence of &quot;from&quot; or as the divergence &quot;from&quot; &quot;to&quot; . This reflects the asymmetry in Bayesian inference, which starts &quot;from&quot; a prior and updates &quot;to&quot; the posterior . Another common way to refer to formula_39 is as the relative entropy of &quot;with respect to&quot; or the information gain from over .

